bug.short_desc: [ErrorHandling] Poor status message, details for job errors

long_desc.thetext: Created attachment 86231 Example 1 with Eclipse 3.4 M4
Created attachment 86233 Example 2 with Eclipse 3.4 M4

In both of these examples, I find the Eclipse 3.2.2 behavior produces a good result. The dialog title is the job name, the description is the status message. If the status is a multi-status, the details show the child status message.
See also bug 211933, things are even worse when the status handler reports a multi-status with severity that is not ERROR.
Created attachment 88956 Another sample screen shot, from I20080205-0010

I agree with the original description. I have an RCP application built on eclipse 3.3, so it's important that I can present end-users with error messages that are both informative and presented well in the UI.
Ideally I'd even be able to simply tell eclipse how to present an IStatus to the user (is there a way to do this already?) instead of using the dialogs you see in the attached screenshots.
I also don't like the addition of the timestamp in the error dialog. For most operations this won't matter and it's just more text the end-user doesn't care to see. I think it should be hidden in the details elsewhere (including information such as the full stack traces for each exception of an IStatus, rather than just the text). Of course I'm not sure off-hand what the best way to present all of this to the user would be...
